    "description": "Keep the last N messages in a rolling window — the simplest conversation memory.",
    "guidance": "Windowed memory automatically maintains a sliding window of the most recent N messages. When the window is full and a new message arrives, the oldest message is dropped.\n\nThis is the right choice when:\n• You want simple conversation context without storage overhead\n• Recent context matters more than full history\n• You're building CLI chatbots or session-scoped assistants\n\nThe chat() function pattern shown here is the canonical BoxLang AI conversation loop:\n1. Add the user message to memory\n2. Call aiChat() with the full memory history\n3. Add the AI response to memory\n4. Repeat\n\nFor multi-user scenarios, pass userId and conversationId to isolate conversations:\naiMemory(\"windowed\", userId: session.userId, conversationId: \"main-chat\", config: { maxMessages: 20 })",
    "output": "> Hello! What can you help me with today?\nHi! I'm your BoxLang AI assistant. I can help you with coding questions, explain BoxLang concepts, review your code, or answer general programming questions. What would you like to explore?\n\n> What's a closure in BoxLang?\nA closure in BoxLang is a function that captures variables from its surrounding scope. Example:\n\n    multiplier = ( factor ) => ( n ) => n * factor\n    double = multiplier( 2 )\n    println( double( 5 ) )  // 15\n\n> Can you show me a more practical example?\nSure! Here's a real-world closure for building URL query strings:\n\n    makeUrl = ( base ) => ( params ) => base & \"?\" & params.map( (k,v) => k & \"=\" & v ).toList( \"&\" )\n    apiUrl = makeUrl( \"https://api.example.com/search\" )\n    println( apiUrl({ q: \"boxlang\", limit: 10 }) )",
    "docsUrl": "https://ai.ortusbooks.com/main-components/memory.md",
    "provider": "openai"
}
*/

// Create a windowed memory that keeps the last 10 messages
memory = aiMemory( "windowed", { maxMessages: 10 } )

// Seed the system persona
memory.add( aiMessage().system(
    "You are a friendly BoxLang expert assistant. Be concise and always include code examples."
) )

// The conversation loop
function chat( userInput ) {
    memory.add( aiMessage().user( userInput ) )
    response = aiChat( memory.getAll() )
    memory.add( aiMessage().assistant( response ) )
    return response
}

// Simulate a multi-turn conversation
questions = [
    "Hello! What can you help me with today?",
    "What's a closure in BoxLang?",
    "Can you show me a more practical example?"
]

for ( question in questions ) {
    println( "> " & question )
    println( chat( question ) )
    println( "" )
}
